# Fusion-middleware

A painless solution to make the communication between TDP application and Fusion application for launch .Rom builders.

# Overview

![Screenshot](./assets/Schema.png)

Middleware functions can perform the following tasks:
  - Connection electron with front-end.
  - Open fusion .Roms
  - Make events.
  - Call .dll functions.

# Get started

## Requirements

 * [lib ffi](https://github.com/node-ffi/node-ffi)  comes bundled with node-ffi; it does *not* need to be installed on your system.
 * [electron-rebuild](https://github.com/electron/electron-rebuild)  package to rebuild native Node.js modules against the currently installed Electron version.
 * Make sure you've installed all the [necessary build
tools](https://github.com/TooTallNate/node-gyp#installation) for your platform,
then invoke:
Source Install / Manual Compilation
-----------------------------------

## (Optional) To compile from source it's easiest to use

[`node-gyp`](https://github.com/TooTallNate/node-gyp):

``` bash
$ npm install -g node-gyp
```

Now you can compile `node-ffi`:

``` bash
$ git clone git://github.com/node-ffi/node-ffi.git
$ cd node-ffi
$ node-gyp rebuild
```

## Basic

electron.js
``` javascript
//Import electron.
const {FMElectro} = require('fusion-middleware');
...
function createWindow() {
  ....
  //Last line
  new FMElectron().bootstrap();
}
```

Angular Service example:

``` javascript
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { Observable, Subject } from 'rxjs';
import { FMFront, FMConstants} from 'fusion-middleware';
import { IpcRenderer } from 'electron';

@Injectable()
export class MiddlewareService {

    private subject = new Subject<any>();
    private readonly _ipc: IpcRenderer | undefined = undefined;
    private fmFront:FMFront| undefined = undefined;

    constructor() {
        if (window.require) {
            try {
                this._ipc = window.require('electron').ipcRenderer;
            } catch (e) {
                throw e;
            }
        } else {
            console.warn('Electron\'s IPC was not loaded');
        }
        this.fmFront = new FMFront(this._ipc);
    }

    bootstrap():void{
        //Handshaking event.
        this.fmFront.bootstrap();
        //Set events.
        this.setEvents(); 
        var model = {
            planId: 1,
            planVersionId: 3,
            AiepId: 1,
            romByteArray: ''
        };
        setTimeout(()=>{
            this.openDocument(model);
        },5000);
    }

    openDocument(model:any):void{
        this.fmFront.open(model);
    }

    private setEvents():void{
        for(let property in FMConstants.FRONT_EVENTS){
            let frontEvent = FMConstants.FRONT_EVENTS[property];
            console.log("Add EVENT: " + frontEvent);
            this.fmFront.on(frontEvent, (event, arg)=>{
                console.log("EVENT: " + frontEvent);
                console.log(arg);
                this.subject.next({ event: frontEvent, model:arg });
            });
        }
    }

    getEvents(): Observable<any> {
        return this.subject.asObservable();
    }

}
```

# Licence
One of the middleware features is to be able to check the Fusion licence. For this task, the middleware checks the ppsecure.lic allocated in somewhere into the PC. 
With this in mind, we have got one parameter to check the licence: APPLICATION_CONSTANTS.FILE_LICENCE_PATH, this parameter is the actual licence path. This paramter is mandatory.
In the Front-end library we have got the next function: <>.checkLicence(). This method could launch the follows events:
 * FRONT_EVENTS.LICENCE_CORRECT
 * FRONT_EVENTS.LICENCE_DOESNT_EXISTS
 * FRONT_EVENTS.LICENCE_WARN_DATE
 * FRONT_EVENTS.LICENCE_EXPIRED

Please checks the events documentation.

2. Run `npm install` to install requirements.

4. Code your Angular side.
5. Deployment.
